Flight logbook has been officially turned on. I have 2.3 hours of flight records ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I have to describe what it's like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a motorcycle/4x4 and a boat at 4000 feet in the air.
On the ground, the situation changes in an instant. The ground has a certain degree of instability, so you need a motorcycle/4x4.
Actually, you might not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, it's controlled by the feet, not the control stick. It uses the rudder pedal and brakes. It's not a car.
When flying in the air, you'll feel the bumps and vibrations, feeling like sailing on the water. Although you can control the airplane, sometimes the airflow will make you a bit dizzy. Therefore, you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like sailors adapt to sailing.
By the way, there's another little anecdote:
Flying is very tiring. Today, my back and legs ache severely, feeling like I've been to the gym to exercise.
This is not as simple as taking a Sunday drive in the car. In my opinion as a beginner, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, have a happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet in the air.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stalling and slow flight.
Today's weather wasn't very stable, but it was super exciting. We practiced slow flight and stalling. Our ground speed dropped to 16 miles/hour, and our airspeed was still 65 miles/hour.
Today the weather was clear, and although the high altitude was a bit foggy, the visibility was still great.
